Cairo contracts are defined using `#[starknet::contract]` and implement interfaces defined with `#[starknet::interface]`. Storage variables are declared within a `#[storage]` struct. Mappings can be used for storage, for example, `Map<KeyType, ValueType>`.

To interact with a `Map` storage variable, you can use `self.map_name.entry(key).read()` to retrieve a value and `self.map_name.entry(key).write(value)` to set a value.

To get the address of the account that called the current function, use `starknet::get_caller_address()`.

Assertions can be used for checks and error handling. If an `assert` condition is false, the program will panic with the provided message. For example: `assert(condition, 'Error message');`.

**Example of Storage and Map usage:**
```cairo
use starknet::ContractAddress;
use starknet::storage::{StoragePointerReadAccess, StoragePointerWriteAccess, StoragePathEntry, Map};
use starknet::get_caller_address;

#[starknet::interface]
pub trait IRegistry<TContractState> {
    fn register_data(ref self: TContractState, data: felt252);
    fn get_user_data(self: @TContractState, user: ContractAddress) -> felt252;
}

#[starknet::contract]
pub mod Registry {
    use starknet::ContractAddress;
    use starknet::storage::*; // Wildcard import for storage
    use starknet::get_caller_address;

    #[storage]
    pub struct Storage {
        user_data_map: Map<ContractAddress, felt252>, // A mapping to store user-specific data
    }

    #[abi(embed_v0)]
    pub impl RegistryImpl of super::IRegistry<ContractState> {
        fn register_data(ref self: ContractState, data: felt252) {
            let caller = get_caller_address();
            self.user_data_map.entry(caller).write(data);
        }

        fn get_user_data(self: @ContractState, user: ContractAddress) -> felt252 {
            self.user_data_map.entry(user).read()
        }
    }
}
